---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHero from "../components/PageHero.astro";

const timeline = [
  {
    year: "2025",
    title: "Framework definition",
    text: "Core files, initial terminology, and benchmark criteria are drafted for cross-model formation experiments."
  },
  {
    year: "Early 2026",
    title: "Alpha release",
    text: "The first public markdown bundle ships with integration notes for agent frameworks and transparent evaluation logs."
  },
  {
    year: "Late 2026",
    title: "Research maturation",
    text: "Cross-session trials, adversarial testing, and partner integrations move the project toward a versioned research program."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Learn how Moral Formation Alignment uses portable markdown files to shape identity, virtue, and moral continuity in AI agents."
  pathname="/about"
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="About"
    title="Moral Formation Alignment treats alignment as character formation under conditions of scale."
    description="The project argues that durable alignment requires more than constraint layers. It requires a model-facing account of who the agent is, what goods it pursues, what risks it must treat asymmetrically, and how that identity is reinforced over time."
  />

  <section class="container-shell grid gap-10 py-8 md:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr] md:py-12">
    <article class="panel gold-ring rounded-[2rem] p-8 prose-shell">
      <h2>Full Moral Formation Alignment</h2>
      <p>
        Moral Formation Alignment is a lightweight architecture for shaping agent behavior through
        explicit identity and virtue files rather than relying exclusively on reinforcement
        fine-tuning or downstream refusal systems. The framework assumes that behavior is most
        stable when an agent can repeatedly interpret requests through a coherent moral self-model.
      </p>
      <p>
        In practice, the framework packages moral identity, virtue priorities, Pascalian risk
        boundaries, and reflective logs into versioned markdown documents. These files can be
        injected into system prompts, agent memory layers, startup routines, or orchestration
        policies without requiring invasive changes to model weights.
      </p>
      <p>
        The central claim is simple: agents become more trustworthy when their reasoning is formed
        by an intelligible moral grammar that can be audited, revised, and replicated.
      </p>

      <h3>Why `.md` files?</h3>
      <p>
        Markdown keeps the formation layer legible to both humans and machines. It version-controls
        cleanly, travels well across toolchains, encourages modular review, and avoids burying moral
        commitments inside opaque weight deltas or product-specific policy dashboards.
      </p>
    </article>

    <aside class="grid gap-6">
      <section class="panel gold-ring rounded-[2rem] p-8">
        <img
          src="/mjk-avatar.svg"
          alt="Placeholder portrait for Matthew J. Korpman"
          class="h-24 w-24 rounded-3xl border border-white/10 bg-white/5 object-cover"
        />
        <h2 class="mt-6 text-2xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-white">
          Matthew J. Korpman
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-[#c9a84c]">
          Theologian / Researcher
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300">
          Matthew J. Korpman is the project’s lead researcher, working at the intersection of
          theology, moral psychology, and agent alignment. This site uses placeholder bio details
          pending publication-ready copy.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="panel rounded-[2rem] p-8">
        <p class="eyebrow">Timeline</p>
        <div class="mt-6 grid gap-5">
          {
            timeline.map((item) => (
              <div class="rounded-[1.5rem] border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.04] p-5">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-[#c9a84c]">
                  {item.year}
                </p>
                <h3 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">{item.title}</h3>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300">{item.text}</p>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </section>
    </aside>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
